39. What is timeout in Jenkins pipeline?

Timeout is a feature in Jenkins pipelines that allows you to specify a time limit for a stage or a block of code.
 If the execution of that stage or block exceeds the specified time limit, it will be aborted and marked as a failure. This can be useful for preventing builds from hanging indefinitely due to issues such as infinite loops, long-running processes, or unresponsive external services. By using the timeout directive in a Jenkins pipeline, you can ensure that your builds do not exceed a reasonable time limit and can fail gracefully if they do. For example, if you want to set a timeout of 30 minutes for a stage, you can use the following syntax:

              pipeline {
                  agent any
                  stages {
                      stage('Long Running Task') {
                          steps {
                              timeout(time: 30, unit: 'MINUTES') {
                                  // long-running task steps
                              }
                          }
                      }
                  }
              }

